<div id="review_690501348" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/690501348" />
    <a title="Magali" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18875408-magali"><img alt="Magali" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1475950258p2/18875408.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/690501348?book_show_action=true">Aug 09, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Magali" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Magali" href="/user/show/18875408-magali">Magali</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780064473545" href="/book/show/34288.The_Time_of_the_Ghost">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18875408-magali?shelf=to-reread">to-reread</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer690501348" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2642742442384186242">The first time I read this book I thought the best part about it was the brilliant and subtle way this unusual ghost story unfolds: &quot;There&apos;s been an accident,&quot; it begins, and we (and the titular ghost) spend the next few hundred pages trying to trace the steps that led there. <br/><br/>In other words, the first time I read this book, I read it as a ghost story with deep roots in mythology that was told exceptionally well. And it is certainly that (in fact it&apos;s a master class in how to make the most of a t</span>
  <span id="freeText2642742442384186242" style="display:none">The first time I read this book I thought the best part about it was the brilliant and subtle way this unusual ghost story unfolds: "There's been an accident," it begins, and we (and the titular ghost) spend the next few hundred pages trying to trace the steps that led there. <br /><br />In other words, the first time I read this book, I read it as a ghost story with deep roots in mythology that was told exceptionally well. And it is certainly that (in fact it's a master class in how to make the most of a third person limited narrator). But this time, I took my time instead of rushing to get to the end, and I was treated to a beautiful and fairly tragic account of four extremely neglected girls who acted out (or in) and took control of their own destinies in very different ways. Unfortunately, one of the consequences of their actions was an accident that threatens to tear them apart. <br /><br />To say more than the above would be to spoil the experience of reading this book--everything in it has its own time and place. But I can't recommend it enough -- to mystery fans, to myth lovers, to devotees of DWJ, to little girls with big dreams, to grown women who feel lost, to anyone who loves a good story. It's gut-wrenching and heartwarming and beautiful. <br /><br />Original review from August 2013: The flow of the narrative of this book was pretty brilliant. It really hooks you and then holds you there until you're finished. I loved it. <br /><br />However, this is the only book of DWJ's I've ever felt like rereading wouldn't be worthwhile. At least, not until I've forgotten enough of it to enjoy the plot unwrapping piece by piece. The genius of this book is in the storytelling.<br /><br />I refuse to say anything more because of spoilers, but I wish I could wipe my memory and enjoy it from the beginning all over again!</span>
  <a data-text-id="2642742442384186242" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


