<div id="review_1128959766" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1128959766" />
    <a title="Alethea" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/34131573-alethea"><img alt="Alethea" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1408526021p2/34131573.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1128959766?book_show_action=true">Dec 10, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alethea" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alethea" href="/user/show/34131573-alethea">Alethea</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1128959766" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16277600513014655769">I finally have a spare moment (or so I tell myself, refusing to look at the stack of assignments glaring at me…) to catch up on four months worth of reviews, and it feels good to get back on track. As always, my usual disclaimer: please keep in mind that it has been a considerable while since I’ve read this. <br/>The Time of the Ghost definitely hit the creepy factor for me. After putting down the book, a chill lingered in my bones. It was a new sensation for an avid Diana Wynne Jones reader, though </span>
  <span id="freeText16277600513014655769" style="display:none">I finally have a spare moment (or so I tell myself, refusing to look at the stack of assignments glaring at me…) to catch up on four months worth of reviews, and it feels good to get back on track. As always, my usual disclaimer: please keep in mind that it has been a considerable while since I’ve read this. <br />The Time of the Ghost definitely hit the creepy factor for me. After putting down the book, a chill lingered in my bones. It was a new sensation for an avid Diana Wynne Jones reader, though I am glad that the freaky cover deterred me as a child (and a-still-child at heart older girl) from picking this up - The Chamber of Secrets gave a five year old me nightmares, and Pretty Little Liars (the TV show) saw a young teen me &amp; cousin scream during their first all-nighter. <br />I feel the blurb was slightly spoilery and let confusion loose (I put a different edition’s Goodreads blurb in to spare you). I feel that without that spoiler I would have enjoyed the book more. <br />The character growth in this was beautiful in a way on Diana Wynne Jones could accomplish. I love how every time I fist read her books, I go in with the murky lenses of the main character and get caught off guard when she removes them, causing a dawning sense of recognition and awe. <br />It’s saddening to realize that with every un-read book of Diana’s, I grow closer to having finished them all - and with them, it sometimes seems, my childhood. Then I reach for my Diana shelf and take out a well-read volume to start again.<br />You can also find this review and a hodge-podge of bibliophilia on my Booklr. :)</span>
  <a data-text-id="16277600513014655769" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


